{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\n\nCreate `examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md` — the shared TDD test-design standard — and wire it into the three skills at the point each incorporates testing. Written in the skills' voice, with the 'scale ceremony to the bug' principle explicit.\n\n**Reference mechanism (canonical file + byte-identical per-skill copies, drift-gated).** `shared/test-design.md` is the canonical copy; each consuming skill directory ships a REAL FILE `<skill>/test-design.md` that must be byte-identical to it. Every SKILL.md references `test-design.md` in its OWN directory — the same same-directory companion-file pattern rebar-debug already uses for `llm-behavioral-taxonomy.md` — so a skill resolves the standard in every load context (repo checkout, a symlinked skill dir in a user skills location, a plain copy, a zip download, any OS), with no symlinks and no user-/machine-specific paths anywhere in the repo. Divergence is prevented by a new gating unit test `tests/unit/test_skill_shared_sync.py` that asserts each copy is byte-identical to the canonical file — it runs under `make test`, an existing gating CI command, mirroring the repo's regenerate-and-diff drift-gate convention (prompt-index, public-types, env-vars). Symlinks were considered and rejected: Windows checkouts without symlink support and GitHub zip archives materialize a symlink as a one-line text file, and copying a single skill directory leaves it dangling. The README documents the convention: edit the canonical file, then sync the copies (`for s in rebar-debug rebar-implement rebar-brainstorm; do cp examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md examples/claude-skills/$s/test-design.md; done`).\n\nThe shared file covers:\n- Existing-coverage inventory before authoring: the required artifact is a RED oracle, which may be an existing failing test, an existing test strengthened into RED form, or a new test only when nothing covers the behavior. Search by contract wording, public entry point, implementation symbol, error text, and bug/regression identifier; read the nearest tests.\n- A test contract card frozen before test code, with scaled fields: contract + citation, bug-triggering preconditions, production path, tier + why lower is insufficient, observable postcondition, CI gate are always required; negative control, collateral invariants, recovery, fault injection apply conditionally (stateful/atomicity/concurrency work).\n- Test-tier selection rule: the smallest tier that still crosses every component in the proven mechanism, with the bug-class -> tier table (unit / producer-consumer contract / real CLI subprocess / real git repos / multi-process with deterministic barrier / parent-child subprocess / kill-and-restart crash recovery / stateful verified fake / behavioral eval). Work spanning several bug classes takes the tier per mechanism-component. At planning time the tier rule is a readiness check, never a deferral: acceptance criteria name both the observable oracle and the tier, and a plan whose mechanism is too unclear to pick a tier carries an unresolved design decision that must be resolved (research, a spike, a clarifying question) before the ticket is recorded.\n- 'Trigger the mechanism, assert the contract': arrange conditions that force the mechanism through the smallest production path crossing the faulty seam; assert the public/contractual consequence, never mock call counts, private helpers, intermediate payloads, or source text.\n- Minimum behavioral oracle: prove the fixture preconditions; assert an exact behavioral postcondition (not is-not-None / nonempty / no-exception); collateral invariants for stateful operations; a clean retry where the contract is atomicity/recoverability.\n- Contrast case: default for input-class defects and stateful operations (nearest passing control / second representative input, parameterized where a family applies); justified omission allowed for trivially single-point bugs.\n- Fault realism: the injected fault must occur inside the code whose recovery/cleanup is under test (fail the real second rename, not a top-level wrapper); race tests must synchronize with a barrier/pipe/marker/failpoint, never timing-only sleeps as the primary mechanism.\n- Prove the test gates: the runner collects the node; it runs (not SKIP/XFAIL) in the supported CI environment; any temporary xfail is strict=True with a removal condition; the test runs under a gating CI command.\n- Defect-seeded mutation: derive the mutation from the confirmed root cause (re-introduce the exact defect), not an arbitrary negation.\n- LLM-surface evals: pinned model/settings, paired before/after prompts, multiple samples with a predeclared threshold and reported failure rates, plus a negative control — quantified rates, never one RED and one GREEN sample.\n\nSkill integration (each SKILL.md references `test-design.md` in its own directory, resolved by its committed byte-identical copy):\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md`: Step 4 becomes 'Design and prove a RED oracle' — inventory first, contract card, tier rule, then RED with proven preconditions, loading the shared file at Phase 2 entry. Step 4's existing LLM-surface paragraph is updated to cite the shared file's quantified-eval requirements as the governing RED-artifact standard, superseding its current single-eval description. Step 5's mutation check becomes defect-seeded, and the fixer handoff list gains a fourth item — the frozen contract card (intended postcondition + invariants) — appended after 'confirmed root cause, evidence, original reproduction steps', while test fixture/assertions stay held out. `llm-behavioral-taxonomy.md` is checked for any single-eval RED-artifact wording and, where present, gains a pointer to the shared standard's quantified-eval requirements so the two files cannot disagree.\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md`: Phase 4a gains an explicit instruction sentence — before deriving the specification, work from `test-design.md` in this skill's directory for oracle design (coverage inventory, tier selection, oracle completeness, gating proof) — and Phase 4b's authoring text cites it for the oracle-minimum checks; the held-out structure (4c/4d/4e) is unchanged.\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-brainstorm/SKILL.md`: in the existing 'Before recording tickets, read the project's plan-review gate' section, add: before recording any ticket whose acceptance criteria will include or reference testing, verification, or behavioral oracles, read the shared file — when in doubt, read it (the cost is one file read; the benefit is correctly-shaped ACs that name the observable oracle).\n- `examples/claude-skills/README.md`: document the shared/ + copies convention (canonical file, byte-identical copies, the sync one-liner, the gating drift test).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md` exists as a regular file and covers every bullet above (inventory, contract card, tier table + per-mechanism-component rule + planning-readiness (no tier deferral) rule, trigger/assert rule, oracle minimum, contrast default, fault realism, gating proof, defect-seeded mutation, LLM evals) with the scale-to-the-bug principle stated. Prove: `grep -c 'RED oracle\\|contract card\\|tier\\|collateral\\|fault\\|gating\\|defect-seeded' examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md` >= 7 plus a section-by-section read against the bullet list.\n- [ ] For each of rebar-debug, rebar-implement, rebar-brainstorm: `examples/claude-skills/<skill>/test-design.md` is a regular file byte-identical to the canonical copy. Prove: `for s in rebar-debug rebar-implement rebar-brainstorm; do cmp examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md examples/claude-skills/$s/test-design.md; done` succeeds and `git ls-files -s examples/claude-skills | grep 120000` is empty.\n- [ ] `tests/unit/test_skill_shared_sync.py` asserts byte-identity of every copy against the canonical file, FAILS when a copy diverges or is missing (verified RED once by perturbing a copy, then restored), and is collected under `make test`. Prove: `.venv/bin/pytest tests/unit/test_skill_shared_sync.py -q` green + the recorded RED evidence in a ticket comment.\n- [ ] rebar-debug Step 4 is retitled to RED-oracle design. Prove: `grep -n 'Design and prove a RED' examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md` hits within the `## Step 4` heading line.\n- [ ] rebar-debug Step 4's LLM-surface paragraph defers to the shared eval standard. Prove: `grep -n -A3 'LLM-surface' examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md` shows `test-design.md` cited in that paragraph.\n- [ ] rebar-debug Step 5 hands the fixer the contract card as a fourth handoff item without exposing held-out test code. Prove: `grep -n -A3 'Hand fix subagent only' examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md` (or the current handoff sentence) lists root cause, evidence, reproduction steps, and the contract card — and no test path/file.\n- [ ] rebar-debug Step 5's mutation check is defect-seeded. Prove: `grep -n 'defect-seeded\\|re-introduce' examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md` hits inside the mutation-check bullet.\n- [ ] rebar-implement Phase 4a/4b cite the shared file as specified. Prove: `grep -n -C2 'test-design.md' examples/claude-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md` shows the hits inside the 4a/4b sections (context lines show the 4a/4b headings or their text).\n- [ ] rebar-brainstorm's 'Before recording tickets' section directs reading the shared file with the when-in-doubt trigger. Prove: `grep -n -C3 'test-design.md' examples/claude-skills/rebar-brainstorm/SKILL.md` shows the hit inside that section.\n- [ ] `examples/claude-skills/README.md` documents the convention. Prove: `grep -n 'test-design\\|byte-identical\\|cp examples/claude-skills/shared' examples/claude-skills/README.md` shows the canonical-file note and the sync one-liner.\n- [ ] No user-/machine-specific paths. Prove: `git grep -n '/Users/\\|joeoakhart' -- examples/claude-skills tests/unit/test_skill_shared_sync.py` returns nothing.\n- [ ] `make lint` and `.venv/bin/pytest tests/unit/test_skill_shared_sync.py -q` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783886623508126001,"uuid":"dd2a364d-a550-4586-8f50-93b07e449476"}